    en: "When a car is towed by the city, towed by a private company, or repossessed by a lender, the owner has a specific set of rights. New York General Business Law 399-v requires private parking lots with five or more spaces to post the operator's contact info and the tow company's contact info before any vehicle can be towed or booted. For city or police tows, the owner can usually get the car back by paying the outstanding tickets, tow fee, and storage, and can contest the tickets at a hearing. For repossessions, UCC Article 9 requires notice before sale, a right to redeem by paying off the loan, and a commercially reasonable sale. A repo that involves a 'breach of the peace' — force, threats, or breaking into a locked garage — is unlawful."
